events.description: King Richard I of England gives Portsmouth its first royal charter.
events.html: • 1194 – King Richard I of England gives Portsmouth its first royal charter.[1]

events.description: William de Braose is hanged by Prince Llywelyn the Great.
events.html: • 1230 – William de Braose is hanged by Prince Llywelyn the Great.

events.description: Anne Boleyn, Queen of England, is arrested and imprisoned on charges of adultery, incest, treason and witchcraft.
events.html: • 1536 – Anne Boleyn, Queen of England, is arrested and imprisoned on charges of adultery, incest, treason and witchcraft.

events.description: John Knox returns from exile to Scotland to become the leader of the nascent Scottish Reformation.
events.html: • 1559 – John Knox returns from exile to Scotland to become the leader of the nascent Scottish Reformation.

events.description: Mary, Queen of Scots, escapes from Lochleven Castle.
events.html: • 1568 – Mary, Queen of Scots, escapes from Lochleven Castle.[2]

events.description: The King James Version of the Bible is published for the first time in London, England, by printer Robert Barker.
events.html: • 1611 – The King James Version of the Bible is published for the first time in London, England, by printer Robert Barker.

events.description: Afonso Mendes, appointed by Pope Gregory XV as Latin Patriarch of Ethiopia, arrives at Beilul from Goa.
events.html: • 1625 – Afonso Mendes, appointed by Pope Gregory XV as Latin Patriarch of Ethiopia, arrives at Beilul from Goa.[3]

events.description: King Charles II of England grants a permanent charter to the Hudson's Bay Company to open up the fur trade in North America.
events.html: • 1670 – King Charles II of England grants a permanent charter to the Hudson's Bay Company to open up the fur trade in North America.

events.description: Outbreak of the Peninsular War: The people of Madrid rise up in rebellion against French occupation. Francisco de Goya later memorializes this event in his painting The Second of May 1808.
events.html: • 1808 – Outbreak of the Peninsular War: The people of Madrid rise up in rebellion against French occupation. Francisco de Goya later memorializes this event in his painting The Second of May 1808.

events.description: The Siege of Cuautla during the Mexican War of Independence ends with both sides claiming victory.
events.html: • 1812 – The Siege of Cuautla during the Mexican War of Independence ends with both sides claiming victory.

events.description: After anchoring nearby, Captain Charles Fremantle of HMS Challenger, declares the Swan River Colony in Australia.
events.html: • 1829 – After anchoring nearby, Captain Charles Fremantle of HMS Challenger, declares the Swan River Colony in Australia.

events.description: American Civil War: Stonewall Jackson is wounded by friendly fire while returning to camp after reconnoitering during the Battle of Chancellorsville. He succumbs to pneumonia eight days later.
events.html: • 1863 – American Civil War: Stonewall Jackson is wounded by friendly fire while returning to camp after reconnoitering during the Battle of Chancellorsville. He succumbs to pneumonia eight days later.

events.description: Peruvian defenders fight off the Spanish fleet at the Battle of Callao.
events.html: • 1866 – Peruvian defenders fight off the Spanish fleet at the Battle of Callao.

events.description: The April Uprising breaks out in Ottoman Bulgaria.
events.html: • 1876 – The April Uprising breaks out in Ottoman Bulgaria.

events.description: Cree and Assiniboine warriors win the Battle of Cut Knife, their largest victory over Canadian forces during the North-West Rebellion.
events.html: • 1885 – Cree and Assiniboine warriors win the Battle of Cut Knife, their largest victory over Canadian forces during the North-West Rebellion.

events.description: Menelik II, Emperor of Ethiopia, signs the Treaty of Wuchale, giving Italy control over Eritrea.
events.html: • 1889 – Menelik II, Emperor of Ethiopia, signs the Treaty of Wuchale, giving Italy control over Eritrea.

events.description: Closing ceremony of the Intercalated Games in Athens, Greece.
events.html: • 1906 – Closing ceremony of the Intercalated Games in Athens, Greece.

events.description: The first game of the Negro National League baseball is played in Indianapolis.
events.html: • 1920 – The first game of the Negro National League baseball is played in Indianapolis.

events.description: Germany's independent labor unions are replaced by the German Labour Front.
events.html: • 1933 – Germany's independent labor unions are replaced by the German Labour Front.

events.description: World War II: Following the coup d'état against Iraq Crown Prince 'Abd al-Ilah earlier that year, the United Kingdom launches the Anglo-Iraqi War to restore him to power.
events.html: • 1941 – World War II: Following the coup d'état against Iraq Crown Prince 'Abd al-Ilah earlier that year, the United Kingdom launches the Anglo-Iraqi War to restore him to power.

events.description: World War II: The Soviet Union announces the fall of Berlin.
events.html: • 1945 – World War II: The Soviet Union announces the fall of Berlin.

events.description: World War II: The surrender of Caserta comes into effect, by which German troops in Italy cease fighting.
events.html: • 1945 – World War II: The surrender of Caserta comes into effect, by which German troops in Italy cease fighting.

events.description: World War II: The US 82nd Airborne Division liberates Wöbbelin concentration camp finding 1,000 dead prisoners, most of whom starved to death.
events.html: • 1945 – World War II: The US 82nd Airborne Division liberates Wöbbelin concentration camp finding 1,000 dead prisoners, most of whom starved to death.

events.description: World War II: A death march from Dachau to the Austrian border is halted by the segregated, all-Nisei 522nd Field Artillery Battalion of the U.S. Army in southern Bavaria, saving several hundred prisoners.
events.html: • 1945 – World War II: A death march from Dachau to the Austrian border is halted by the segregated, all-Nisei 522nd Field Artillery Battalion of the U.S. Army in southern Bavaria, saving several hundred prisoners.

events.description: A De Havilland Comet makes the first jetliner flight with fare-paying passengers, from London to Johannesburg.
events.html: • 1952 – A De Havilland Comet makes the first jetliner flight with fare-paying passengers, from London to Johannesburg.

events.description: Berthold Seliger launches a rocket with three stages and a maximum flight altitude of more than 100 kilometres (62 mi) near Cuxhaven. It is the only sounding rocket developed in Germany.
events.html: • 1963 – Berthold Seliger launches a rocket with three stages and a maximum flight altitude of more than 100 kilometres (62 mi) near Cuxhaven. It is the only sounding rocket developed in Germany.

events.description: Vietnam War: An explosion sinks the American aircraft carrier USNS Card while it is docked at Saigon. Two Viet Cong combat swimmers had placed explosives on the ship's hull. She is raised and returned to service less than seven months later.
events.html: • 1964 – Vietnam War: An explosion sinks the American aircraft carrier USNS Card while it is docked at Saigon. Two Viet Cong combat swimmers had placed explosives on the ship's hull. She is raised and returned to service less than seven months later.

events.description: First ascent of Shishapangma, the fourteenth highest mountain in the world and the lowest of the Eight-thousanders.
events.html: • 1964 – First ascent of Shishapangma, the fourteenth highest mountain in the world and the lowest of the Eight-thousanders.

events.description: The British ocean liner Queen Elizabeth 2 departs on her maiden voyage to New York City.
events.html: • 1969 – The British ocean liner Queen Elizabeth 2 departs on her maiden voyage to New York City.

events.description: ALM Flight 980 ditches in the Caribbean Sea near Saint Croix, killing 23.
events.html: • 1970 – ALM Flight 980 ditches in the Caribbean Sea near Saint Croix, killing 23.[4]

events.description: In the early morning hours a fire breaks out at the Sunshine Mine located between Kellogg and Wallace, Idaho, killing 91 workers.
events.html: • 1972 – In the early morning hours a fire breaks out at the Sunshine Mine located between Kellogg and Wallace, Idaho, killing 91 workers.

events.description: Falklands War: The British nuclear submarine HMS Conqueror sinks the Argentine cruiser ARA General Belgrano.
events.html: • 1982 – Falklands War: The British nuclear submarine HMS Conqueror sinks the Argentine cruiser ARA General Belgrano.

events.description: Chernobyl disaster: The City of Chernobyl is evacuated six days after the disaster.
events.html: • 1986 – Chernobyl disaster: The City of Chernobyl is evacuated six days after the disaster.

events.description: Cold War: Hungary begins dismantling its border fence with Austria, which allows a number of East Germans to defect.
events.html: • 1989 – Cold War: Hungary begins dismantling its border fence with Austria, which allows a number of East Germans to defect.

entities.name: Removal of Hungary's border fence with Austria

events.description: During the Croatian War of Independence, the Army of the Republic of Serb Krajina fires cluster bombs at Zagreb, killing seven and wounding over 175 civilians.
events.html: • 1995 – During the Croatian War of Independence, the Army of the Republic of Serb Krajina fires cluster bombs at Zagreb, killing seven and wounding over 175 civilians.

entities.name: Army of the Republic of Serb Krajina

events.description: The European Central Bank is founded in Brussels in order to define and execute the European Union's monetary policy.
events.html: • 1998 – The European Central Bank is founded in Brussels in order to define and execute the European Union's monetary policy.

events.description: Panamanian general election: Mireya Moscoso becomes the first woman to be elected President of Panama.
events.html: • 1999 – Panamanian general election: Mireya Moscoso becomes the first woman to be elected President of Panama.

events.description: President Bill Clinton announces that accurate GPS access would no longer be restricted to the United States military.
events.html: • 2000 – President Bill Clinton announces that accurate GPS access would no longer be restricted to the United States military.

events.description: The Yelwa massacre concludes. It began on 4 February 2004 when armed Muslims killed 78 Christians at Yelwa, Nigeria. In response, about 630 Muslims were killed by Christians on May 2.
events.html: • 2004 – The Yelwa massacre concludes. It began on 4 February 2004 when armed Muslims killed 78 Christians at Yelwa, Nigeria. In response, about 630 Muslims were killed by Christians on May 2.

events.description: Cyclone Nargis makes landfall in Burma killing over 138,000 people and leaving millions of people homeless.
events.html: • 2008 – Cyclone Nargis makes landfall in Burma killing over 138,000 people and leaving millions of people homeless.

events.description: Chaitén Volcano begins erupting in Chile, forcing the evacuation of more than 4,500 people.
events.html: • 2008 – Chaitén Volcano begins erupting in Chile, forcing the evacuation of more than 4,500 people.

events.description: Osama bin Laden, the suspected mastermind behind the September 11 attacks and the FBI's most wanted man, is killed by the United States Navy SEALs in Abbottabad, Pakistan.
events.html: • 2011 – Osama bin Laden, the suspected mastermind behind the September 11 attacks and the FBI's most wanted man, is killed by the United States Navy SEALs in Abbottabad, Pakistan.

events.description: An E. coli outbreak strikes Europe, mostly in Germany, leaving more than 30 people dead and many others are taken ill.
events.html: • 2011 – An E. coli outbreak strikes Europe, mostly in Germany, leaving more than 30 people dead and many others are taken ill.

events.description: A pastel version of The Scream, by Norwegian painter Edvard Munch, sells for $120 million in a New York City auction, setting a new world record for a work of art at auction.
events.html: • 2012 – A pastel version of The Scream, by Norwegian painter Edvard Munch, sells for $120 million in a New York City auction, setting a new world record for a work of art at auction.[5]

events.description: Two mudslides in Badakhshan, Afghanistan, leave up to 2,500 people missing.
events.html: • 2014 – Two mudslides in Badakhshan, Afghanistan, leave up to 2,500 people missing.
